<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="141" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,2027]" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">
<emphasis box="[636,661,1784,1807]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">—</emphasis>
recorded by the author in the company of M. Gascoigne-Pees at the Čakor pass on 
<date box="[329,494,1818,1846]" pageId="13" pageNumber="141" value="2017-07-14">July 14th 2017</date>
(
<figureCitation box="[513,586,1821,1846]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1443,1465]" captionTargetBox="[169,1417,522,1421]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[169,1417,522,1421]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erebia alberganus, a pair from Čakor pass." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1195501/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). The species was widespread and in good numbers in suitable habitats. Specimens were mainly worn. In the neighbouring countries the species is present in 
<collectingCountry box="[1107,1178,1858,1883]" name="Serbia" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">Serbia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1233,1332,1858,1883]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
, on Stara Planina (
<bibRefCitation box="[251,425,1893,1918]" pageId="13" pageNumber="141" refId="ref7819" refString="Abadjiev, S. (2001) An Atlas of the Distribution of the Butterflies in Bulgaria (Lepidoptera: Hesperioidea &amp; Papilionoidea). Pensoft Publishers, Sofia-Moscow, 335 pp." type="book">Abadjiev 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[438,666,1893,1918]" pageId="13" pageNumber="141" refId="ref10368" refString="Popovic, M., Duric, M., Franeta, F. &amp; Verovnik, R. (2013) On the extremely rich butterfly fauna (Lepidoptera: Rhopalocera) on the soth-eastern foothills of Stara Planina Mts in Serbia. Phegea, 41 (4), 74 - 81." type="journal article">
Popović 
<emphasis box="[539,597,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
), and in 
<collectingCountry box="[768,892,1893,1918]" name="Macedonia" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">
<collectingRegion box="[768,892,1893,1918]" country="Greece" name="Dytiki Makedonia" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">Macedonia</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
in the Šar Planina massif (
<bibRefCitation box="[1204,1379,1893,1918]" pageId="13" pageNumber="141" refId="ref9990" refString="Melovski, D. (2002) Daily butterflies (Rhopalocera) on Sar Planina Mt. Bulletin of the Biology Students' Research Society, 2, 131 - 144." type="journal article">Melovski 2002</bibRefCitation>
) and Korab mountain (
<bibRefCitation box="[348,539,1930,1955]" pageId="13" pageNumber="141" refId="ref9867" refString="Louy, D., Habel, J. C., Ulrich, W. &amp; Schmitt, T. (2013) Out of the Alps: The biogeography of a disjunctly distributed mountain butterfly, the Almond eyed ringlet Erebia alberganus (Lepidoptera, Satyrinae). Journal of Heredity, 105, 28 - 38. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jhered / est 081" type="journal article">
Louy 
<emphasis box="[415,472,1930,1955]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="141">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). The discovery of this species on Čakor pass comes as a surprise, since the area has been surveyed by several entomologists (
<bibRefCitation box="[662,804,1965,1990]" pageId="13" pageNumber="141" refId="ref9367" refString="Kocak, A. O. (1989) On the butterflies of Yugoslavia (Lepidoptera). Centre for Entomological Studies, Priamus, 5 (1 / 2), 3 - 22." type="journal article">Koçak 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[816,966,1965,1990]" pageId="13" pageNumber="141" refId="ref8940" refString="Jaksic, P. (2003 b) Fauna leptira (Lepidoptera: Zygaenidae, Hesperioidea i Papilionoidea) metohijskih Prokletija. In: Amidzic, L., Jankovic, M. M. &amp; Jaksic, P. (Eds.), Metohijske Prokletije, prirodna i kulturna bastina. Zavod za zastitu prirode Srbije, Beograd, pp. 234 - 261." type="book chapter">Jakšić 2003b</bibRefCitation>
; Weiss 1975) and the species is evidently common in suitable habitats.
</paragraph>
